280
00:13:19,166 --> 00:13:22,000
Their Japanese name
means firefly stones.

281
00:13:25,083 --> 00:13:26,375
[MIRAI] A lens?

282
00:13:26,583 --> 00:13:27,791
Like, for glasses?

283
00:13:27,791 --> 00:13:30,125
This one was made
by polishing fluorite,

284
00:13:30,333 --> 00:13:33,625
so it's different in refractive
index and dispersion.

285
00:13:33,833 --> 00:13:36,166
So, point is, it's
a professional grade

286
00:13:36,375 --> 00:13:38,291
lens with high
precision, making

287
00:13:38,500 --> 00:13:42,250
it perfect for our ridiculously
upgraded fluorite telescope.

288
00:13:45,791 --> 00:13:47,125
[GEN] Oh-ho-ho.

289
00:13:47,333 --> 00:13:48,500
Antastic-fay.

290
00:13:48,708 --> 00:13:49,875
I feel like I can practically

291
00:13:50,083 --> 00:13:50,958
see the moon's craters.

292
00:13:51,166 --> 00:13:52,041
Ha.

293
00:13:52,250 --> 00:13:53,333
You know, if we were to make

294
00:13:53,541 --> 00:13:54,791
a bigger one of these,

295
00:13:54,791 --> 00:13:56,833
I bet we could even
spot Why-man up there.

296
00:13:57,041 --> 00:13:59,291
[chuckles] Fat
chance we'll find

297
00:13:59,500 --> 00:14:01,333
a crystal big enough for that.

298
00:14:01,541 --> 00:14:04,791
And it'll be a while before
we're making it in a lab.

299
00:14:05,000 --> 00:14:07,458
As soon as we get a lock
on Why-man's whereabouts,

300
00:14:07,666 --> 00:14:10,916
we'll be flying this baby
straight up there to meet him.

301
00:14:11,125 --> 00:14:12,875
You made a rocket?

302
00:14:13,083 --> 00:14:15,791
Though, it's kind of--

303
00:14:16,000 --> 00:14:17,875
[CHELSEA] That thing's
mega small, yo.

304
00:14:18,083 --> 00:14:20,916
Pretty sure I'm the only one
of us who could fit inside.

305
00:14:21,125 --> 00:14:23,500
You're not quite
as tiny as you used to be.

306
00:14:23,708 --> 00:14:25,750
Oh, that's a good point.

307
00:14:25,958 --> 00:14:28,000
You're looking
at a model rocket.

308
00:14:28,208 --> 00:14:31,291
Now we just need to slap
on Xeno's jet engine prototype,

309
00:14:31,500 --> 00:14:34,083
then pick a launching spot
and give it a test drive.

310
00:14:34,291 --> 00:14:36,333
It truly is awe-inspiring.

311
00:14:36,541 --> 00:14:39,625
I realize it's not to scale,
but seeing it with my own eyes

312
00:14:39,833 --> 00:14:41,166
makes it much easier
to believe we're

313
00:14:41,375 --> 00:14:42,916
making steady strides
that will eventually

314
00:14:43,125 --> 00:14:46,208
take us from the stone
world to the moon.

315
00:14:46,416 --> 00:14:48,250
We still have
something to figure out.

316
00:14:48,458 --> 00:14:50,375
We're going to need
dead accurate trajectory

317
00:14:50,583 --> 00:14:54,458
calculations, which means
the next city we need to build

318
00:14:54,666 --> 00:14:55,875
is clear as day.

319
00:14:57,583 --> 00:15:00,208
The city of Math in India.

320
00:15:00,416 --> 00:15:01,708
The city of Math, huh?

321
00:15:01,916 --> 00:15:02,791
Sure.

322
00:15:03,000 --> 00:15:04,083
India has always been known

323
00:15:04,291 --> 00:15:05,583
for having insanely advanced

324
00:15:05,791 --> 00:15:07,291
mathematics education.

325
00:15:07,500 --> 00:15:09,750
That's the reason they're
recognized on a global scale

326
00:15:09,958 --> 00:15:12,250
